---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const schemaSnippet = `sixpack::schema! {
    messages {
        id id
        conversation_id id
        body text

        lookup conversation_id many
    }
}

db.write(messages::add(messages::Row {
    id: "m1".to_owned(),
    conversation_id: "cv1".to_owned(),
    body: "typed local state".to_owned(),
}))?;

let thread = db.get(messages::by::conversation_id("cv1"))?;`;
---

<BaseLayout
  title="sixpack"
  description="A local-first table database layer for typed Rust applications."
>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container hero">
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow">local-first table storage</p>
        <h1>the local database humans can read.</h1>
        <p class="lead">
          sixpack is for apps that want fast local data without turning their
          state into a black box. Write with typed Rust APIs, inspect the files
          when something breaks, and keep the hot path binary.
        </p>
        <div class="actions">
          <a class="button primary" href="/docs">Read the docs</a>
          <a class="button" href="https://github.com/sixpack/sixpack">View source</a>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="panel diagram" aria-label="sixpack storage flow">
        <div class="node"><strong>schema</strong><span>declared tables and lookups</span></div>
        <div class="node"><strong>typed API</strong><span>selectors and changes, no SQL strings</span></div>
        <div class="node focus"><strong>.6</strong><span>readable append-only source data</span></div>
        <div class="node focus"><strong>runtime .6b map</strong><span>hot ids, lookups, counts, and edits</span></div>
        <div class="node"><strong>compact .6b</strong><span>rebuildable binary cache snapshot</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="grid">
        <article class="card">
          <h3>Schema-shaped API</h3>
          <p>No SQL strings in application code. The schema defines rows, selectors, and write changes.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="card">
          <h3>Readable truth</h3>
          <p>`.6` segments remain the canonical append source. Generated files can be discarded and rebuilt.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="card">
          <h3>Binary hot state</h3>
          <p>Runtime `.6b` maps keep ids, lookups, counts, and edits off full-table traversal paths.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container prose">
      <h2>Current benchmark snapshot</h2>
      <p>
        Results are from the current local hot-path benchmark: 10,000 rows
        preloaded once, one live database handle, and 1,000 operations per
        Criterion iteration.
      </p>
      <table class="metric-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Operation</th>
            <th>sixpack</th>
            <th>SQLite</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>get by id</td><td>~0.50 ms</td><td>~3.19 ms</td></tr>
          <tr><td>count</td><td>~26 us</td><td>~3.10 ms</td></tr>
          <tr><td>add one-by-one</td><td>~38.7 ms</td><td>~301.1 ms</td></tr>
          <tr><td>add batched</td><td>~4.28 ms</td><td>~6.83 ms</td></tr>
          <tr><td>edit one-by-one</td><td>~38.8 ms</td><td>~5.69 ms</td></tr>
          <tr><td>edit batched</td><td>~5.13 ms</td><td>~0.52 ms</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p>
        SQLite remains much faster for large transactional update batches. The
        current sixpack advantage is narrow: readable append data with fast
        generated runtime projections for local state workloads.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container prose">
      <h2>Minimal syntax</h2>
      <pre><code>{schemaSnippet}</code></pre>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
